x4freetext: A 310 mm thick ORTEC surface barrier detector
of 44 mm2 active area, coupled to an ORTEC 101-210 low
noise amplification system was used. The detector
subtended an angle from the target of about 0.03 rad in
the scattering plane and a solid angle of about
The target was lithium fluoride (Li2F2) with a fluorine
thickness of about 0.3 mg/cm2 evaporated onto a
supporting carbon foil of similar thickness. A few
percent of natural oxygen, which tended to obscure the
weak inelastic scattering to the first excited state of
19F, was also present. A second target of calcium
fluoride (CaF2) evaporated onto a carbon foil was used
in the normalization of the angular distributions to
absolute differential cross section.
Normalization of the yields to absolute differential
cross sections was done by measuring the angular
distribution of elastically scattered protons from the
natural calcium of the calcium fluoride target at
4.258 MeV bombarding energy.
